elements.content: Four novel interesting coordination polymers, [Cd3(bix)3(SSA)2(H2O)4] n (1), [Co(bix)2(HSSA)(H2O)·H2O] n (2), [Ni(bix)2(HSSA)(H2O)·H2O] n (3) and [Mn(bix)2·(HSSA)·2H2O] n (4) (bix = 1,4-bis(imidazol-1-ylmethyl)-benzene; H3SSA = 5-sulfosalicylic acid), have been synthesized under hydrothermal conditions and structurally characterized. Polymer 1 features a two-dimensional (2D) infinite layer framework built from tri-cadmium clusters, which is further stacked along the c-axis via strong interlayer hydrogen-bond interactions to form a three-dimensional (3D) network. Both polymers 2 and 3 exhibit one-dimensional (1D) double-stranded chains, which are connected by strong hydrogen-bond interactions along the c-axis to result in 2D layers; in addition, the layers are further stacked along the b-axis by π−π interactions. Polymer 4 also possesses 1D double-stranded chains. It is noteworthy that ligand HSSA in compound 4 is not coordinated to the metal ions but only acts as an anion moiety to compensate the charge balance. The fluorescent properties for these compounds were investigated and the mechanisms were validated by density functional theory (DFT) calculations on the experimental geometries. In addition, 4 is nearly paramagnetic, whereas weak ferromagnetic interactions between M(II) (M = Co, Ni) ions have been found in 2 and 3.

Introduction

Recently, remarkable progress has been made in the area of molecular inorganic-organic hybrid compounds owing to their fascinating structural diversities and potential applications, such as magnetism, host-guest chemistry, catalysis, and functional porous materials. Some weak interactions, such as hydrogen bonding and π-π stacking interactions, also greatly affect the structures of coordination complex. Moreover, they may link low-dimensional entities into high-dimensional supramolecular networks.

elements.content: Ligand 5-sulfosalicylic acid (H3SSA, Chart ) is a simple but interesting compound, which has three potential coordinating groups:  −OH, −CO2H, and −SO3H. Therefore, it can coordinate to metal ions with different modes. Additionally, H3SSA and its derivatives have been found to have great fluorescence potency not only in the solution but also in the solid state. Some of functional derivatives from H3SSA have been reported recently. With the aim of preparing novel materials with beautiful architecture and excellent fluorescence properties, we started to elaborate new coordination polymers constructed from 5-sulfosalicylic acid (H3SSA) and 1,4-bis(imidazol-1-ylmethyl)-benzene (bix, Chart ). In this text, we report four novel coordination polymeric complexes, [Cd3(bix)3(SSA)2(H2O)4] n (1), [Co(bix)2(HSSA)(H2O)·H2O] n (2), [Ni(bix)2(HSSA)(H2O)·H2O] n (3), and [Mn(bix)2·(HSSA)·2H2O] n (4), which demonstrate different fluorescence and magnetic properties in the solid state. Interestingly, H3SSA exhibits three different coordination modes in these compounds (model I, II, and III show the existing form of the H3SSA in compound 1, 2, and 4, respectively, Chart ).

 Crystal Structure of 1. A single-crystal X-ray diffraction study reveals that 1 adopts a 2-D supramolecular structure. As depicted in Figure a, there exist two types of coordination environments around the cadmium ions in the crystal structure: Cd1 has distorted octahedral coordination sphere, which is defined by two bix nitrogen atoms occupying the apical positions, while the basal plane is completed by two carboxylate oxygen atoms and two aqua ligands; the Cd2 center is situated at an inversion center and adopts an octahedral coordination environment, which is surrounded by two carboxylate oxygen and two phenol oxygen atoms, as well as two nitrogen donors from different bix.

elements.content: Both the carboxylate and phenolic oxygen atoms of SSA ligand are coordinated to metal centers. Cd1 and Cd2 atoms are bridged by μ2-O from a carboxylate moiety with Cd1···Cd2 separations of 4.146 Å to form a dimer unit, which is further interconnected with another Cd1 through another carboxylate oxygen bridge to form the trimetallic cluster (Figure b). For the bix ligand to which N5 belongs, two terminal imidazole groups are in trans conformation and have their planes steeply tilted 91.4° with respect to the average plane of phenyl ring. In the case of the bix containing N1, two terminal imidazole groups are also in trans conformation, and the dihedral angles between the imidazole ring planes and the least-squares plane of phenyl group are 72.2 and 72.6°, respectively. The bidentate bix molecules establish a physical bridge between the tri-cadmium cluster, imposing Cd···Cd separations of 15.81 Å for one configuration and 14.01 Å for the other. Progression of the trimetallic clusters through bix yields a two-dimensional (2D) infinite layer framework in the ab plane (Figure b).

elements.content: It has been suggested that the emission bands in d10 metal complexes originate from nd → (n+1)s or nd → (n+1)p electronic transitions, which are often mixed with metal-to-ligand charge-transfer (MLCT), ligand-to-metal charge-transfer (LMCT), and ligand-to-ligand (LLCT) charge transfer. To assign the emission bands, we carried out MO calculations on the free H3SSA, HSSA2- in the complex 4, and mononuclear [Cd(SSA)2(mz)2]4- species (the basic geometry of the complex 1). According to the MO calculations, the red shift of complex 4 originates from the deprotonated H3SSA. As depicted in Figure , for H3SSA, the HOMO is associated with π-bonding orbital from the phenyl ring, while the LUMO+1 are mainly associated with π-antibonding orbital. (The LUMO of H3SSA is n-antibonding orbital, which is mainly from sulfonate group.) For HSSA2-, its LUMO is similar to the LUMO+1 of H3SSA, while the HOMO is π-bonding orbital mainly composed of carboxylate oxygen and phenyl rings. The calculation gaps (HOMO − LUMO+1 for H3SSA, HOMO − LUMO for HSSA2-) are 4.89 and 4.58 eV; correspondingly, the experimentally measured emission energy values are ca. 3.20 and 3.10 eV.

elements.content: Thermal Analyses and XRD Patterns. Compound 1 is stable up to ca. 270 °C, and above the temperature, the organic groups start to burn (Figure ). Because there exist strong hydrogen-bonding interactions among free water, coordination water, and sulfonate oxygen atoms for compound 2, the preliminary weight loss attributed to the gradual release of free aqua legands begins at ca. 140 °C. The weight loss of 4.72% below 227 °C (calcd 4.57%) is attributed to loss of one lattice water and one coordination water in the compound. Then at about 230 °C, the main framework begins to collapse. Compound 3 has the same decomposition process as compound 2. For 4, the weight loss of 4.79% below 192 °C (calcd 4.61%) corresponds to the loss of two coordinated water molecules per formula. The compound is stable up to 220 °C, where the framework structures begin to collapse. The purity of complexes is confirmed by X-ray power diffraction analyses, in which the experimental spectra of complexes 1−4 are almost consistent with their simulated spectra (Figures S2−S5, Supporting Information). As depicted in Figure S5, the diffraction profiles of 4 after heating at 190 °C are almost same with the as-synthesized compound, which supports the fact that compound 4 remains intact after removal of the water molecules. Whereas after the compound is heated at 230 °C, the diffraction peaks of the compound are absent for 4.

elements.content: Magnetic Properties. The χm T value of compound 2 is 3.12 emu K mol-1 at 300 K, which is significantly larger than the spin-only value of 1.875 emu K mol-1 for Co(II) (S = 3/2). (see Supporting Information, Figure S6). Fitting the data above 30 K using the Curie−Weiss law gives a Curie constant C = 3.376 emu K mol-1 and a negative Weiss constant θ = −22.54 K. Commonly, this kind of behavior of χm T and negative θ value may indicate the occurrence of dominant antiferromagnatic coupling between the spin carriers. However, the spin−orbit coupling of the 4T1g state of the Co(II) ion in an octahedral ligand field can normally lead to a negative θ value and a decrease in χm T at high temperatures. From the structure information, we know that the Co(II) ions are well separated, and two Co(II) ions in the asymmetric unit are surrounded by a similar chemical environment, so we can treat the magnetic data by considering a mononuclear Co2+ with a spin−orbit coupling parameter λ (H = −λLS) in a molecular-field approximation. The χmono for mononuclear Co2+ in an octahedral environment can be calculated from eqs S1 and S2, and considering the molecular field approach with zJ as the total exchange coupling between Co2+ ions, we can fit our experiment data with eq S319 (see Supporting Information). In these equations, N, g, β, k B, and T have their usual meanings. The parameter A gives a measure of the crystal field strength relative to the interelectronic repulsions and is equal to 1.5 for a weak crystal field, 1.32 for a free ion, and 1.0 for a strong field. The best fit (Figure S6, Supporting Information, experimental data above 30 K) gives λ = −156 cm-1, A = 1.22, g = 2.26, and zJ = 1.22 cm-1 with R = 8.1 × 10-5. The positive zJ value indicates the weak ferromagnetic coupling between the Co(II) ions.

elements.content: In summary, four novel polymers were constructed from H3SSA and bix, and for all these compounds, hydrogen-bonding interactions play an important role in the formation of supramolecular architecture. Interestingly, different coordination modes of H3SSA result in different crystal packing of the complexes, which exhibit various fluorescent and magnetic properties. In particular, complex 1 displays significant enhancement of the fluorescent intensity, which is approximated three to four times larger than that of the free H3SSA. The strong fluorescence emission makes it a potentially useful photoactive material. According to the results of calculation, the emission was assigned to ligand-to-ligand charge-transfer (LLCT) with little mixing of the metal-to-ligand charge-transfer (MLCT) characters. Additionally, compounds 2−4 exhibit different magnetic properties:  4 is nearly paramagnetic, whereas weak ferromagnetic interactions have been found in 2 and 3.

Luminescent Properties. The emission spectra of complexes 1−4 and ligand H3SSA in the solid state are investigated at room temperature under the same situations. As depicted in Figure , excitation at 348 nm leads to strong blue-fluorescent emission band at 388 nm for free H3SSA, which is comparable to those values reported previously. Complex 1 exhibits much more intense emission bands at 394 nm upon excitation at 343 nm. For compound 4, the emission intensity is relatively weaker than that of H3SSA. No clear photoluminescence emissions of 2 and 3 were observed at room temperature. The luminescence emissions of 2 and 3 may be quenched by Co(II) and Ni(II) ions. It is clear that a bathochromic shift of emission occurs in 1 and 4. Furthermore, complex 1 exhibits significant enhancement of the fluorescent intensity, which is approximately three to four times that of the free H3SSA ligand.

Thermal Analyses and XRD Patterns. Compound 1 is stable up to ca. 270 °C, and above the temperature, the organic groups start to burn (Figure ). Because there exist strong hydrogen-bonding interactions among free water, coordination water, and sulfonate oxygen atoms for compound 2, the preliminary weight loss attributed to the gradual release of free aqua legands begins at ca. 140 °C. The weight loss of 4.72% below 227 °C (calcd 4.57%) is attributed to loss of one lattice water and one coordination water in the compound. Then at about 230 °C, the main framework begins to collapse. Compound 3 has the same decomposition process as compound 2. For 4, the weight loss of 4.79% below 192 °C (calcd 4.61%) corresponds to the loss of two coordinated water molecules per formula. The compound is stable up to 220 °C, where the framework structures begin to collapse. The purity of complexes is confirmed by X-ray power diffraction analyses, in which the experimental spectra of complexes 1−4 are almost consistent with their simulated spectra (Figures S2−S5, Supporting Information). As depicted in Figure S5, the diffraction profiles of 4 after heating at 190 °C are almost same with the as-synthesized compound, which supports the fact that compound 4 remains intact after removal of the water molecules. Whereas after the compound is heated at 230 °C, the diffraction peaks of the compound are absent for 4.

Magnetic Properties. The χm T value of compound 2 is 3.12 emu K mol-1 at 300 K, which is significantly larger than the spin-only value of 1.875 emu K mol-1 for Co(II) (S = 3/2). (see Supporting Information, Figure S6). Fitting the data above 30 K using the Curie−Weiss law gives a Curie constant C = 3.376 emu K mol-1 and a negative Weiss constant θ = −22.54 K. Commonly, this kind of behavior of χm T and negative θ value may indicate the occurrence of dominant antiferromagnatic coupling between the spin carriers. However, the spin−orbit coupling of the 4T1g state of the Co(II) ion in an octahedral ligand field can normally lead to a negative θ value and a decrease in χm T at high temperatures. From the structure information, we know that the Co(II) ions are well separated, and two Co(II) ions in the asymmetric unit are surrounded by a similar chemical environment, so we can treat the magnetic data by considering a mononuclear Co2+ with a spin−orbit coupling parameter λ (H = −λLS) in a molecular-field approximation. The χmono for mononuclear Co2+ in an octahedral environment can be calculated from eqs S1 and S2, and considering the molecular field approach with zJ as the total exchange coupling between Co2+ ions, we can fit our experiment data with eq S319 (see Supporting Information). In these equations, N, g, β, k B, and T have their usual meanings. The parameter A gives a measure of the crystal field strength relative to the interelectronic repulsions and is equal to 1.5 for a weak crystal field, 1.32 for a free ion, and 1.0 for a strong field. The best fit (Figure S6, Supporting Information, experimental data above 30 K) gives λ = −156 cm-1, A = 1.22, g = 2.26, and zJ = 1.22 cm-1 with R = 8.1 × 10-5. The positive zJ value indicates the weak ferromagnetic coupling between the Co(II) ions.

Figure S7 of Supporting Information shows the magnetic behavior of 3 in the form of a χm T vs T plot. At 300 K, χm T is 1.23 emu K mol-1 per Ni(II). Upon cooling the sample to 16 K, the χm T values increase continuously to a maximum of 1.96 emu K mol-1, indicating the presence of ferromagnetic coupling in 3. Upon further cooling of 3 below 16 K, the χm T values decrease to 0.52 emu K mol-1 at 1.8 K, which could be due to the interchain antiferromagnetic interactions and/or the zero-field splitting of the ground state. The data were analyzed by the Curie−Weiss law, which led to parameters C = 1.23 emu K mol-1 and θ = 2.43. The small positive value also indicates weak ferromagnetic interactions in 3.

As Figure S8 (Supporting Information) shows, the value of χm T of complex 4 at 300 K is 4.48 emu K mol-1, which is as expected for one uncoupled Mn(II) ion. The χm T vs T values of 4 are constant in the entire temperature range, which shows the compound is nearly paramagnetic. The data were analyzed by the Curie−Weiss law, which led to the parameters C = 4.48 emu K mol-1 and θ = −0.61 K. The small negative θ value indicates there exist extremely weak antiferromagnetic interactions between neighboring Mn(II) ions.
